06218nam a22008295i 9781478022039DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780220397 a10.1515/97814780220392doi  a(DE-B1597)609913  a(OCoLC)1261317779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM892b.D433 2021eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a303.422300aDecay /ced. by Ghassan Hage. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (189 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. STATES OF DECAY -- t1. Forever “Falling Apart”: Semiotics and Rhetorics of Decay -- t2. Trash and Treasure: Pathologies of Permanence on the Margins of Our Plastic Age -- t3. Infrastructure as Decay and the Decay of Infrastructure -- t4. The Waterfall at the End of the World: Earthquakes, Entropy, and Explanation -- t5. “Vile Corpse”: Urban Decay as Human Beauty and Social Pollution -- t6. Decay or Fresh Contact? The Morality of Mixture after War’s End -- t7. Seeds of Decay -- t8. Discourses of Decay in Settler Colonial Australia -- t9. Decay as Decline in Social Viability among Ex-Militiamen in Lebanon -- t10. Relational Decay: White Helpers in Australia’s Indigenous Communities -- t11. Decay, Rot, Mold, and Resistance in the US Prison System -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn eleven sharp essays, the contributors to Decay attend to the processes and experiences of symbolic and material decay in a variety of sociopolitical contexts across the globe. They examine decay in its myriad manifestations—biological, physical, organizational, moral, political, personal, and social and in numerous contexts, including colonialism and imperialism, governments and the state, racism, the environment, and infrastructure. The volume's topics are wide in scope, ranging from the discourse of social decay in contemporary Australian settler colonialism and the ways infrastructures both create and experience decay to cultural decay in the aftermath of the Sri Lankan civil war and the relations among individual, institutional, and societal decay in an American high-security prison. By using decay as a problematic and expounding its mechanisms, conditions, and temporalities, the contributors provide nuanced and rigorous means to more fully grapple with the exigencies of the current sociopolitical moment.Contributors. Cameo Dalley, Peter D. Dwyer, Akhil Gupta, Ghassan Hage, Michael Herzfeld, Elise Klein, Bart Klem, Tamara Kohn, Michael Main, Fabio Mattioli, Debra McDougall, Monica Minnegal, Violeta Schubert  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAnthropological ethics. 0aDegenerationxPolitical aspects. 0aDegenerationxSocial aspects. 0aPolitical culture. 0aSocial change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aDalley, Cameo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Peter D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Akhil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHage, Ghassan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHage, Ghassan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerzfeld, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Elise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlem, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohn, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMain, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato